RECOMPENSE OR RECOVERY IN

RECONTINUANCE seems to be used to
signify that a person has recovered an incorporeal hereditament of which he had
been wrongfully deprived. Thus, “A. is disseised of a manor, whereunto an advowson
is appendant, an estranger [i. e., neither A.
nor the disseisor] usurps to the advowson;
if the disseisee [i. e., A.] enter into the manor,
the advowson is recontinued again, which
was severed by the usurpation. * * * And so note a diversity between a recontinuance and a remitter; for a remitter cannot be properly, unless there be two titles;
but a recontinuance may be where there is
but one.” Co. Litt. 863a; Sweet.

